    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Rumsfeld's Critics, and His Defense</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>James D Poisson letter says it is Defense Secretary Rumsfeld's judgment, not his patriotism or dedication, that is questionable (April 16 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Civilians Reign Over U.S. Military by Tradition and Design'' (news article, April 16) quotes Gen. Peter Pace as saying, ''People can question my judgment or his judgment, but they should never question the dedication, the patriotism and the work ethic of Secretary Rumsfeld.''</p>
        <p>No one has questioned the dedication, patriotism or work ethic of Defense Secretary Donald H. Rumsfeld. Questioning others' virtue is a standard right-wing ploy seldom used by the other side except to deplore lying.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Civilians Reign Over U.S. Military by Tradition and Design'' (news article, April 16) quotes Gen. Peter Pace as saying, ''People can question my judgment or his judgment, but they should never question the dedication, the patriotism and the work ethic of Secretary Rumsfeld.''</p>
        <p>No one has questioned the dedication, patriotism or work ethic of Defense Secretary Donald H. Rumsfeld. Questioning others' virtue is a standard right-wing ploy seldom used by the other side except to deplore lying.</p>
        <p>It is precisely Mr. Rumsfeld's judgment that his critics are questioning. General Pace's rhetoric is the type often used by the Bush administration: create a straw man, knock him down and then avoid the substance of the issue.</p>
        <p>James D. Poisson  Wakefield, R.I., April 16, 2006</p>
      </block>
